1
00:00:01,746 --> 00:00:04,877
Yeah, it's the watermelon, right? I didn't forget.

2
00:00:04,960 --> 00:00:06,839
Then go buy a nice-looking one!

3
00:00:06,923 --> 00:00:09,220
Alright, alright... Sheesh.

4
00:00:09,678 --> 00:00:12,684
Ran's at the Professor's house... Huh?

5
00:00:12,768 --> 00:00:16,066
So, in other words, you, Ms. Kaori Kitazaka...

6
00:00:16,400 --> 00:00:21,077
are an alumna of Jonan University's Mystery Research Society, and a party celebrating the marriage of a fellow alumnus of that same society...

7
00:00:21,160 --> 00:00:22,955
is being held...

8
00:00:23,038 --> 00:00:25,627
starting at 4 o'clock today, but...

9
00:00:25,919 --> 00:00:28,716
you don't know the location of the venue.

10
00:00:28,800 --> 00:00:31,430
The reason being, the party host...

11
00:00:31,514 --> 00:00:33,893
in keeping with the Mystery Research Society name...

12
00:00:33,977 --> 00:00:37,609
sent out invitations drawn as rebus puzzles.

13
00:00:37,693 --> 00:00:39,154
...Is that about right?

14
00:00:39,238 --> 00:00:42,494
Yes. I just couldn't solve the rebus puzzle, no matter what...

15
00:00:42,744 --> 00:00:45,667
and so, by chance, I happened to be passing by...

16
00:00:45,750 --> 00:00:49,007
and I thought perhaps the famous Detective Mori could help...

17
00:00:49,091 --> 00:00:52,681
Ah, I see. Leave it to me.

18
00:00:52,764 --> 00:00:54,643
I, the great detective Kogoro Mori...

19
00:00:54,727 --> 00:00:58,443
will solve this rebus puzzle for you in no time.

20
00:00:58,693 --> 00:01:00,947
Hey, hey, are you sure about this?

21
00:01:01,282 --> 00:01:03,494
...So, what is this rebus puzzle?

22
00:01:03,578 --> 00:01:04,663
Here.

23
00:01:05,540 --> 00:01:06,542
It's this.

24
00:01:07,419 --> 00:01:08,463
Hmm...

25
00:01:09,673 --> 00:01:10,926
Hmm...

26
00:01:12,721 --> 00:01:15,059
Hm? What's this...?

27
00:01:15,310 --> 00:01:19,067
I see. Yeah, this isn't an easy one to crack.

28
00:01:22,407 --> 00:01:28,419
♪~

29
00:01:35,433 --> 00:01:38,439
Cutting through the blackness of shadows and the depth of darkness, the light of deduction!

30
00:01:38,856 --> 00:01:42,572
With the Belfry Tower area as the stage, solve the mystery of the secretive venue!

31
00:01:42,656 --> 00:01:44,033
Seeing through the one and only truth!

32
00:01:44,284 --> 00:01:46,122
Looks like a kid, mind is an adult.

33
00:01:46,205 --> 00:01:49,002
His name is Detective Conan!

34
00:03:13,523 --> 00:03:19,535
~♪

35
00:03:20,744 --> 00:03:27,144
"A Coded Invitation"

36
00:03:27,144 --> 00:03:30,974
I've always been bad with deductions and codes, you see...

37
00:03:31,057 --> 00:03:35,315
Even when I joined the club, the only code I could crack was the "tanuki code."

38
00:03:35,399 --> 00:03:37,152
The "tanuki code"?

39
00:03:37,236 --> 00:03:40,952
It's a basic cipher where you read the text while omitting the character "ta."

40
00:03:41,035 --> 00:03:42,037
Oh!

41
00:03:42,121 --> 00:03:46,296
But if that's the case, why did you join a mystery research society?

42
00:03:47,089 --> 00:03:48,341
Well, that's...

43
00:03:48,425 --> 00:03:50,178
I've got it!

44
00:03:50,262 --> 00:03:53,351
These four fingers, from the pinky to the index finger...

45
00:03:53,436 --> 00:03:55,063
represent train lines.

46
00:03:55,147 --> 00:03:57,611
Huh? Train lines...?

47
00:03:57,694 --> 00:03:58,946
Huh?

48
00:03:59,238 --> 00:04:02,829
You see, train lines have what they call "line colors"...

49
00:04:03,371 --> 00:04:05,752
This yellow pinky is the Sobu Line.

50
00:04:06,169 --> 00:04:08,883
The yellow-green ring finger is the Yamanote Line.

51
00:04:09,342 --> 00:04:12,389
The light blue middle finger is the Keihin-Tohoku Line.

52
00:04:12,891 --> 00:04:16,105
The red index finger represents the Chuo Line.

53
00:04:16,482 --> 00:04:19,655
In other words, the party venue is at the location of the thumbnail, in a place where these four train lines run parallel.

54
00:04:19,738 --> 00:04:24,163
The party venue is at the location of the thumbnail.

55
00:04:25,207 --> 00:04:27,796
Oh, I see! I never would have thought of that.

56
00:04:27,879 --> 00:04:31,219
Hmm... But is there really a place like that?

57
00:04:31,470 --> 00:04:33,432
Unfortunately, no.

58
00:04:33,683 --> 00:04:35,853
But, if you twist your head a little...

59
00:04:38,108 --> 00:04:40,362
The numbers written on this guide map mean...

60
00:04:40,446 --> 00:04:44,120
"Look at a 1:25,000 scale map,"

61
00:04:44,579 --> 00:04:48,629
You place the pinky, the Sobu Line, over this point, Akihabara...

62
00:04:48,713 --> 00:04:52,929
and place the ring finger, the Yamanote Line, and the middle finger, the Keihin-Tohoku Line...

63
00:04:53,012 --> 00:04:56,352
on this line between Akihabara and Kanda.

64
00:04:56,437 --> 00:04:58,566
Then place the index finger, the Chuo Line...

65
00:04:58,649 --> 00:05:01,822
on this line between Ochanomizu and Kanda.

66
00:05:01,905 --> 00:05:06,164
If you do that, the place this thumbnail points to is...

67
00:05:07,416 --> 00:05:08,669
Kanda-Ogawamachi.

68
00:05:09,044 --> 00:05:12,426
Kanda-Ogawamachi? Ah... Then...

69
00:05:12,761 --> 00:05:16,518
this drawing of a river means "Ogawa" (small river), right?

70
00:05:16,602 --> 00:05:20,735
But the fingers on the guide map are stretched out straight.

71
00:05:20,818 --> 00:05:24,116
Your hand, though, is all curled up.

72
00:05:24,200 --> 00:05:26,120
Don't sweat the small stuff!

73
00:05:26,412 --> 00:05:28,208
Oh, brother...

74
00:05:28,501 --> 00:05:29,503
Hm?

75
00:05:31,465 --> 00:05:34,805
Well? Does that location ring any bells?

76
00:05:34,888 --> 00:05:36,182
Yes, it does!

77
00:05:36,558 --> 00:05:40,273
There's a Jonan University hall in the 2-chome district of Kanda-Ogawamachi.

78
00:05:40,483 --> 00:05:41,485
Seriously?

79
00:05:41,568 --> 00:05:42,737
Just as I thought.

80
00:05:42,821 --> 00:05:46,077
That hall must be the party venue, without a doubt.

81
00:05:46,160 --> 00:05:47,622
Amazing, Dad!

82
00:05:47,705 --> 00:05:49,083
Na-ha-ha-ha!

83
00:05:49,375 --> 00:05:51,087
No way...

84
00:05:51,505 --> 00:05:55,095
Thank you very much! Now I can attend the party.

85
00:05:55,428 --> 00:05:56,807
Um, what about your fee...?

86
00:05:56,890 --> 00:05:58,393
Ah, no, no, no, no.

87
00:05:58,477 --> 00:06:02,067
I couldn't possibly accept money for such a simple request.

88
00:06:02,150 --> 00:06:03,487
What? But...

89
00:06:03,571 --> 00:06:05,115
No charge is necessary.

90
00:06:05,908 --> 00:06:09,541
I'm so sorry about that. Well then, if you insist...

91
00:06:09,624 --> 00:06:11,335
(Bump)

92
00:06:11,628 --> 00:06:13,841
Thank you so very much.

93
00:06:13,924 --> 00:06:16,513
If anything else comes up, please feel free to contact us.

94
00:06:16,597 --> 00:06:18,976
Yes, excuse me.

95
00:06:22,232 --> 00:06:24,571
Hm...
(Door closes)

96
00:06:26,157 --> 00:06:28,579
But since we're all making it together...

97
00:06:28,662 --> 00:06:31,167
we should do something on a huge scale, right?

98
00:06:31,250 --> 00:06:33,672
How about making lots of different insects out of paper...

99
00:06:33,756 --> 00:06:36,260
and calling it the "Insect Forest"?

100
00:06:36,344 --> 00:06:39,099
What about an aquarium with lots of fish swimming around?

101
00:06:39,183 --> 00:06:41,605
An airfield would be cool too!

102
00:06:43,984 --> 00:06:46,657
As I suspected, you just can't accept Mori's deduction, can you?

103
00:06:46,740 --> 00:06:47,992
Yeah. To be precise, the Chuo Line's color...

104
00:06:48,409 --> 00:06:52,167
isn't red, it's vermilion, and...

105
00:06:52,250 --> 00:06:58,847
Even if I try swapping in other red, blue, yellow, and green line colored trains
I just can't find a spot that fits.

106
00:06:58,931 --> 00:07:01,478
No matter how I rearrange them...

107
00:07:01,561 --> 00:07:04,024
the location just doesn't match up.

108
00:07:04,400 --> 00:07:06,320
Could it be the subway?

109
00:07:06,404 --> 00:07:08,492
I thought about that too, but...

110
00:07:08,575 --> 00:07:11,790
in the first place, there's no line with a yellow line color.

111
00:07:13,752 --> 00:07:16,340
Huh... A bridge?

112
00:07:16,424 --> 00:07:18,595
Oh... Right.

113
00:07:18,679 --> 00:07:20,766
That left hand, it's...

114
00:07:21,935 --> 00:07:24,691
Oh no, I have to let her know, fast!

115
00:07:24,941 --> 00:07:26,945
Sorry, handle the rest!

116
00:07:27,029 --> 00:07:28,699
Conan?

117
00:07:29,074 --> 00:07:31,245
It seems he's solved it.

118
00:07:31,328 --> 00:07:32,749
Looks like it.

119
00:07:34,544 --> 00:07:38,009
What?! It's not Kanda-Ogawamachi?

120
00:07:38,092 --> 00:07:40,473
Yeah. Look at this map.

121
00:07:40,848 --> 00:07:44,313
The river drawn on that rebus is this Sumida River...

122
00:07:44,396 --> 00:07:46,526
and the colors of the bridges spanning it are...

123
00:07:46,985 --> 00:07:49,156
Kuramae Bridge is yellow.

124
00:07:49,657 --> 00:07:52,370
Umaya Bridge is a yellowish-green.

125
00:07:52,914 --> 00:07:55,001
Komagata Bridge is blue.

126
00:07:56,253 --> 00:07:58,216
Azuma Bridge is red.

127
00:07:58,842 --> 00:08:03,560
In other words, those fingernail colors were pointing to these four bridges!

128
00:08:03,644 --> 00:08:05,230
Wow, Conan!

129
00:08:05,313 --> 00:08:06,357
Mmmph...

130
00:08:06,441 --> 00:08:08,821
You have the copy of the rebus, right?

131
00:08:08,904 --> 00:08:10,406
Hm? Ah, yeah...

132
00:08:10,825 --> 00:08:13,121
If you match the hand's fingernails on this invitation...

133
00:08:13,204 --> 00:08:16,168
to the positions of each of these bridges...

134
00:08:16,252 --> 00:08:18,256
the thumb's position is...

135
00:08:19,258 --> 00:08:23,015
Belfry Tower! Then that's the party venue?

136
00:08:23,099 --> 00:08:27,065
But still, there's a university hall in Kanda-Ogawamachi...

137
00:08:27,149 --> 00:08:30,698
There's no doubt. I called Belfry Tower just a bit ago...

138
00:08:30,781 --> 00:08:32,325
and confirmed it.

139
00:08:32,409 --> 00:08:35,331
They've specially rented out the pre-opening restaurant...

140
00:08:35,415 --> 00:08:38,296
and from 4 o'clock today, Jonan University's Mystery Research Society...

141
00:08:38,379 --> 00:08:40,801
is holding a wedding party there.

142
00:08:40,885 --> 00:08:44,684
Dad, you have to call Ms. Kaori right away and tell her!

143
00:08:44,767 --> 00:08:45,978
Alright, alright.

144
00:08:46,061 --> 00:08:50,821
The number you have dialed is not currently in service...

145
00:08:51,280 --> 00:08:52,450
That's odd.

146
00:08:52,533 --> 00:08:54,119
You got the number wrong.

147
00:08:54,203 --> 00:08:57,417
Dad, you have to call her cell phone, not her home phone.

148
00:08:57,501 --> 00:09:00,089
Ms. Kaori should still be out and about.

149
00:09:00,340 --> 00:09:01,635
Ah, right.

150
00:09:01,718 --> 00:09:03,054
Wait a second.

151
00:09:03,137 --> 00:09:07,813
Why would Ms. Kaori write down a wrong number for her home phone?

152
00:09:07,897 --> 00:09:10,068
Well, she probably just made a careless mistake...

153
00:09:10,151 --> 00:09:12,615
But it's her own home phone number.

154
00:09:12,698 --> 00:09:14,326
Who gets that wrong...?

155
00:09:14,409 --> 00:09:17,040
In that case, she wrote a fake number on purpose.

156
00:09:17,415 --> 00:09:19,086
It happens sometimes.

157
00:09:19,169 --> 00:09:23,010
Some people write down lies because they don't want their family to know they visited a detective agency.

158
00:09:23,094 --> 00:09:24,806
Some people write down lies for that reason.

159
00:09:25,223 --> 00:09:27,645
But Ms. Kaori just wanted to find the location of a wedding party, right?

160
00:09:27,728 --> 00:09:29,691
But Ms. Kaori just wanted to find the location of a wedding party, right?

161
00:09:29,774 --> 00:09:32,404
It's not something bad for her family to know about...

162
00:09:32,488 --> 00:09:35,911
How should I know? Quit your yapping.

163
00:09:35,995 --> 00:09:37,372
(Phone ringing)

164
00:09:37,456 --> 00:09:38,458
Hello?

165
00:09:38,542 --> 00:09:41,380
Ah, hello, is this Ms. Kaori?

166
00:09:41,464 --> 00:09:43,802
It's Mori. Actually...

167
00:09:44,554 --> 00:09:48,687
Oh, I see! I'm here at the university hall in Ogawamachi right now...

168
00:09:48,979 --> 00:09:52,027
and was at a loss because it wasn't the venue.

169
00:09:52,110 --> 00:09:55,325
Belfry Tower, right? Thank you very much!

170
00:09:55,408 --> 00:09:58,205
No problem at all. Take care.

171
00:09:58,874 --> 00:10:01,921
That's good. Looks like she'll make it to the party.

172
00:10:02,422 --> 00:10:07,140
Still, why would Ms. Kaori write her real cell number...

173
00:10:07,223 --> 00:10:10,313
but a fake number for her home phone?

174
00:10:10,856 --> 00:10:13,862
And in the first place, just to find a party venue...

175
00:10:13,945 --> 00:10:16,116
even if she was passing by...

176
00:10:16,200 --> 00:10:18,914
would you normally visit a detective agency?

177
00:10:19,457 --> 00:10:23,590
Hey, did you hear anything about Ms. Kaori's family?

178
00:10:23,673 --> 00:10:26,763
Ah, yeah. Ms. Kaori is single...

179
00:10:26,846 --> 00:10:28,850
and lives with her parents, it seems.

180
00:10:29,184 --> 00:10:33,860
When she wrote her home phone number, did she act strange at all?

181
00:10:33,944 --> 00:10:37,993
Huh? Not at all... Sheesh, you're such a pest.

182
00:10:38,244 --> 00:10:40,916
Ah, wait, now that you mention it, Ms. Kaori...

183
00:10:40,999 --> 00:10:43,295
after writing her cell number...

184
00:10:44,172 --> 00:10:48,097
"Um, should I write my home number, too?"

185
00:10:48,180 --> 00:10:50,686
Yes, if you don't mind.

186
00:10:59,411 --> 00:11:00,581
...which means...

187
00:11:00,664 --> 00:11:03,587
Could it be she only faked the last digit...?

188
00:11:08,179 --> 00:11:11,101
(Phone ringing)

189
00:11:11,185 --> 00:11:12,688
Hello, this is the Kitazaka residence.

190
00:11:13,397 --> 00:11:16,529
Ah! I got so caught up in verifying the number, I didn't think about what to say...

191
00:11:16,613 --> 00:11:18,742
I got so caught up in verifying the number...

192
00:11:18,825 --> 00:11:20,871
Hello?
Ah, um...

193
00:11:20,954 --> 00:11:23,250
My name is Conan Edogawa.

194
00:11:23,334 --> 00:11:25,046
Conan Edogawa?

195
00:11:25,129 --> 00:11:26,925
Wait, Conan?!

196
00:11:27,008 --> 00:11:28,929
Excuse me, just a moment...
Ah, yes.

197
00:11:29,012 --> 00:11:31,726
Hello, Conan? It's Sato from the Metropolitan Police.

198
00:11:31,809 --> 00:11:32,978
Officer Sato?!

199
00:11:33,062 --> 00:11:34,314
What?

200
00:11:43,593 --> 00:11:47,433
I'm here at the Kitazaka house with Officer Takagi right now...

201
00:11:47,935 --> 00:11:50,564
Why are you calling this number, Conan?

202
00:11:50,649 --> 00:11:51,776
Why are you there, Officer Sato?

203
00:11:52,026 --> 00:11:55,241
What are you doing at that house? Did something happen?

204
00:11:55,324 --> 00:11:57,495
Huh? Well, that's...

205
00:11:57,579 --> 00:12:00,126
Hang on, I'll put Kogoro on.

206
00:12:01,336 --> 00:12:04,050
This is Mori. Did something happen at the Kitazaka household?

207
00:12:04,342 --> 00:12:05,553
Mr. Mori...

208
00:12:05,637 --> 00:12:08,434
What's wrong? I'm happy to help if I can.

209
00:12:10,187 --> 00:12:12,901
Actually, a handgun has gone missing.

210
00:12:13,110 --> 00:12:14,905
What? A handgun...?

211
00:12:14,989 --> 00:12:17,828
Yes. The missing weapon is...

212
00:12:17,911 --> 00:12:21,794
an old Imperial Japanese Army Type 14 automatic pistol...

213
00:12:22,378 --> 00:12:26,344
that the homeowner, Michio Kitazaka's father...

214
00:12:26,428 --> 00:12:28,892
Nobuyoshi, had passed away last year...

215
00:12:28,975 --> 00:12:32,315
and they found it while going through his belongings.

216
00:12:33,108 --> 00:12:35,154
Of course, military handguns...

217
00:12:35,237 --> 00:12:38,578
must be reported to the police as soon as they are found, but...

218
00:12:38,953 --> 00:12:41,959
Mr. Michio, as a keepsake of his father...

219
00:12:42,043 --> 00:12:45,592
had carefully stored it away, along with five bullets.

220
00:12:46,009 --> 00:12:49,516
I see. And that's what's gone missing, right?

221
00:12:49,600 --> 00:12:50,602
Yes.

222
00:12:50,936 --> 00:12:53,983
There's no sign of a break-in.

223
00:12:54,067 --> 00:12:55,110
So if someone took it...

224
00:12:55,569 --> 00:12:58,033
the only possibility is their daughter, Kaori.

225
00:12:58,116 --> 00:12:59,118
What?!

226
00:12:59,494 --> 00:13:01,248
Ms. Kaori said today...

227
00:13:01,331 --> 00:13:05,130
she was going to attend a university senior's wedding party...

228
00:13:05,339 --> 00:13:07,803
and left the house late this morning, but...

229
00:13:07,886 --> 00:13:09,765
apparently, the way she was acting then...

230
00:13:10,266 --> 00:13:11,936
seemed deeply troubled.

231
00:13:12,019 --> 00:13:13,021
What?

232
00:13:13,313 --> 00:13:18,198
When we spoke with the family, it seems this senior, a male...

233
00:13:18,282 --> 00:13:22,164
was two-timing Kaori and the person he's marrying, and in the end...

234
00:13:22,916 --> 00:13:25,504
Kaori was apparently dumped.

235
00:13:25,589 --> 00:13:27,759
H-Hey, then that means...

236
00:13:27,843 --> 00:13:31,433
Yes. Her father, Michio, noticed the missing gun...

237
00:13:31,516 --> 00:13:34,940
and tried calling Kaori's cell phone several times, but couldn't get through...

238
00:13:35,024 --> 00:13:38,030
so that's why he contacted the police.

239
00:13:38,322 --> 00:13:41,579
We were just about to start looking into where the wedding party venue is...

240
00:13:41,662 --> 00:13:43,373
We were just about to start looking into where the wedding party venue is...

241
00:13:43,457 --> 00:13:45,461
We know where the party is.

242
00:13:45,544 --> 00:13:47,674
It's Belfry Tower.

243
00:13:50,220 --> 00:13:54,730
But I wonder if it really was Ms. Kaori who took the gun.

244
00:13:54,813 --> 00:13:56,316
When she came to the office...

245
00:13:56,399 --> 00:13:59,238
she was carrying a big clutch bag, remember?

246
00:13:59,322 --> 00:14:00,742
Huh? Yeah.

247
00:14:00,825 --> 00:14:02,871
Well, when she left...

248
00:14:03,455 --> 00:14:04,959
(Bump)

249
00:14:05,501 --> 00:14:09,217
The gun was probably inside that bag.

250
00:14:09,300 --> 00:14:11,847
What?!
And also, Ms. Kaori...

251
00:14:11,931 --> 00:14:15,020
did you notice she was wearing low-heeled shoes?

252
00:14:17,358 --> 00:14:19,697
Ah, yeah. For a party...

253
00:14:19,780 --> 00:14:23,705
I thought it'd be better to wear higher heels.

254
00:14:24,038 --> 00:14:26,543
She wore shoes like that...

255
00:14:26,919 --> 00:14:29,758
to stabilize her body.

256
00:14:30,092 --> 00:14:33,265
So she wouldn't miss her target when firing a gun.

257
00:14:33,348 --> 00:14:36,647
What? Then, as I thought...

258
00:14:37,231 --> 00:14:39,695
Ms. Kaori, who's bad at deductions and codes...

259
00:14:39,778 --> 00:14:42,576
probably joined the Mystery Research Society...

260
00:14:42,659 --> 00:14:45,957
because she liked that senior.

261
00:14:46,249 --> 00:14:49,590
Damn... We're not gonna make it.

262
00:14:50,174 --> 00:14:53,263
What do I do? What do I do?!

263
00:14:53,890 --> 00:14:54,892
Ah...

264
00:14:59,735 --> 00:15:00,862
Conan?

265
00:15:02,114 --> 00:15:06,414
Somehow, with this... Please, don't go through with it.

266
00:16:06,911 --> 00:16:08,371
Huh...!

267
00:16:33,839 --> 00:16:37,012
Ahem, well, thank you all so much for joining us today in such a lively gathering...

268
00:16:37,096 --> 00:16:41,437
thank you so much for coming in such large numbers.

269
00:16:41,521 --> 00:16:44,903
Did you find the party venue easily?

270
00:16:44,987 --> 00:16:46,782
Like we ever could!

271
00:16:46,865 --> 00:16:48,786
Yonekura isn't here yet.

272
00:16:48,869 --> 00:16:51,750
Alright, alright, we'll hear your feedback later...

273
00:16:51,834 --> 00:16:54,840
Now, without further ado, let's call up the bride and groom!

274
00:16:54,923 --> 00:16:56,885
(Applause)

275
00:16:56,969 --> 00:16:59,808
(Party poppers)

276
00:16:59,891 --> 00:17:01,812
(Cheers)

277
00:17:02,229 --> 00:17:03,649
Hah...

278
00:17:04,442 --> 00:17:08,617
First, a greeting from the blissfully happy groom!

279
00:17:08,951 --> 00:17:11,749
Has Ms. Kaori not arrived yet?

280
00:17:12,041 --> 00:17:16,132
No, coming from Kanda-Ogawamachi, she should have been here ages ago.

281
00:17:19,221 --> 00:17:20,390
Ah! Ms. Kaori...!

282
00:17:20,725 --> 00:17:22,645
Ms. Kaori!

283
00:17:26,402 --> 00:17:27,989
Ah... Hah...

284
00:17:35,045 --> 00:17:36,632
Ms. Kaori!

285
00:17:37,549 --> 00:17:39,679
Hm?

286
00:17:50,701 --> 00:17:51,870
No good.

287
00:17:54,751 --> 00:17:56,630
Don't do it, Ms. Kaori!

288
00:18:04,019 --> 00:18:05,731
What were your words for the proposal?

289
00:18:05,815 --> 00:18:08,904
You're really gonna make me say it?

290
00:18:08,988 --> 00:18:09,990
Ah...

291
00:18:17,212 --> 00:18:19,049
K-Kaori?

292
00:18:19,425 --> 00:18:20,761
Ms. Kaori...

293
00:18:30,823 --> 00:18:33,119
Ms. Kaori... Ah!

294
00:18:33,536 --> 00:18:35,625
(Cheers)

295
00:18:36,209 --> 00:18:38,631
Congratulations, Mr. Nagai.

296
00:18:38,714 --> 00:18:41,929
Ah... Thanks, Kaori.

297
00:19:00,340 --> 00:19:03,304
Thank goodness... You didn't go through with it.

298
00:19:03,722 --> 00:19:05,058
Hey, kid.

299
00:19:05,308 --> 00:19:09,693
The old man Kogoro, he went downstairs with the detectives.

300
00:19:09,776 --> 00:19:12,406
Seems they mistook someone else for Ms. Kaori.

301
00:19:20,213 --> 00:19:24,639
When I was about to head to the party venue just now...

302
00:19:26,602 --> 00:19:28,479
(Message received)
Ah!

303
00:19:34,450 --> 00:19:35,703
Ah...

304
00:19:39,847 --> 00:19:42,199
"It's good that you were distinguished as a hairy caterpillar and a smooth caterpillar."

305
00:19:44,386 --> 00:19:47,727
At first, I didn't understand what it said.

306
00:19:48,102 --> 00:19:49,104
But then...

307
00:19:49,563 --> 00:19:53,071
I ignored the "ke" characters, and the "i" characters, and read it.

308
00:19:53,154 --> 00:19:56,620
"It's good you broke up with that kind of man."

309
00:20:01,128 --> 00:20:03,424
In that moment, my surging emotions...

310
00:20:03,508 --> 00:20:06,682
just suddenly vanished, like a tide going out...

311
00:20:08,226 --> 00:20:11,232
I figured, if you could read the "tanuki code," Ms. Kaori...

312
00:20:11,315 --> 00:20:14,113
you would definitely understand.

313
00:20:14,196 --> 00:20:18,706
Huh? So, the person who sent this wasn't Mr. Mori...?

314
00:20:19,206 --> 00:20:20,458
Heh heh.

315
00:20:20,542 --> 00:20:21,837
Conan...

316
00:20:21,920 --> 00:20:23,131
Ms. Kaori!

317
00:20:25,135 --> 00:20:26,763
Hey, Ms. Kaori.

318
00:20:26,847 --> 00:20:30,604
You said you happened to be passing by the office...

319
00:20:30,688 --> 00:20:35,280
but the truth is, you planned from the start to have Kogoro solve it...

320
00:20:35,363 --> 00:20:38,829
and you came to the office with that plan in mind, right?

321
00:20:39,455 --> 00:20:43,589
Yes. I used the famous Detective Mori.

322
00:20:46,010 --> 00:20:47,471
I'm very sorry.

323
00:20:47,722 --> 00:20:50,351
No, no, please don't worry about it.

324
00:20:51,855 --> 00:20:53,399
Ms. Kaori Kitazaka?

325
00:20:53,483 --> 00:20:54,526
Yes.

326
00:20:55,236 --> 00:20:57,909
I'm Sato from the Metropolitan Police, First Investigation Division.

327
00:20:57,992 --> 00:20:59,579
And I'm Takagi.

328
00:21:11,728 --> 00:21:15,527
Ms. Kitazaka, please come with us to headquarters.

329
00:21:15,611 --> 00:21:16,655
Alright.

330
00:21:20,788 --> 00:21:23,417
Hey, kid, your name's Conan, right?

331
00:21:23,961 --> 00:21:27,677
Yeah. Conan Edogawa, detective.

332
00:21:30,724 --> 00:21:33,814
Thank you, little detective.

333
00:21:42,080 --> 00:21:48,092
♪~

334
00:22:55,978 --> 00:23:01,740
~♪

335
00:23:05,371 --> 00:23:09,087
After that, Ms. Kaori and her father, Michio...

336
00:23:09,171 --> 00:23:13,597
were sent to prosecutors for violation of the Firearms and Swords Control Law, but the case was dropped...

337
00:23:13,889 --> 00:23:17,520
and the phantom shooting incident was resolved without incident.

338
00:23:18,230 --> 00:23:21,487
Speaking of which, we were invited by Sonoko tomorrow to...

339
00:23:21,571 --> 00:23:24,326
the Toto Belfry Tower. I'm looking forward to it.

340
00:23:24,577 --> 00:23:25,871
Me too!

341
00:23:25,954 --> 00:23:27,415
I hope the weather's nice.

342
00:23:27,499 --> 00:23:29,879
I'm gonna make a "teru teru bozu" doll.

343
00:23:30,254 --> 00:23:34,054
Ah, man... I have to chaperone these guys again?

344
00:23:37,060 --> 00:23:39,941
I hear there are great restaurants near Belfry Tower...

345
00:23:40,024 --> 00:23:42,863
No one could have imagined...

346
00:23:42,947 --> 00:23:46,830
that a new shooting incident would be waiting for us at that Belfry Tower...

347
00:23:48,124 --> 00:23:51,338
No one had any idea at the time.

348
00:23:51,923 --> 00:23:53,718
Ha ha ha ha...!

349
00:23:54,052 --> 00:23:57,267
Mwa ha ha ha! As expected of the great detective!

350
00:23:57,350 --> 00:24:00,398
To see through the hiding place of this Kaito Kid!

351
00:24:00,691 --> 00:24:03,529
So you've finally shown yourself, Kaito Kid!

352
00:24:05,909 --> 00:24:08,790
Hm? Ah!

353
00:24:12,798 --> 00:24:15,888
Damn it! Where the hell are you?!

354
00:24:15,888 --> 00:24:16,995
Next Conan,

355
00:24:16,995 --> 00:24:19,695
"The Secret of the Kogoro Mouri Statue"

356
00:24:36,895 --> 00:24:39,295
Next Conan's Hint:

357
00:24:39,295 --> 00:24:41,395
"Basketball"

358
00:24:41,395 --> 00:24:42,695
The movie will be released from today.

359
00:24:42,695 --> 00:24:43,995
The theme song is great!

360
00:24:43,995 --> 00:24:45,695
I love the singer too!
